  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_1' aria-label=\" H. Guruswamy & Ors. versus A. Krishnaiah Since Deceased By LRs. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('1','2025','2025_1_764_771','2025INSC53'); ><font size='4'> <strong>H. GURUSWAMY & ORS.<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>A. KRISHNAIAH SINCE DECEASED BY LRS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 1 S.C.R. 764</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 53</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010002352025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Order dated 05.08.2014 passed by the trial court rejecting application filed under Order 9 Rule 13 CPC came to be set aside by the High Court, which was challenged in the present appeal; The appellants submitted that there was a delay of six years (about 2200 days) in itself; and the High Court proceeded to condone the delay of about 2200 days without adverting to any of the reasons assigned by the Trial Court while rejecting application filed for recall. Headnotes&dagger; Limitation &ndash; Rules of limitation are meant to see that the parties do not<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 08-01-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 317/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('1','2025','2025_1_764_771','2025INSC53','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('1','2025','